A Standardized Framework for Elastomer Characterization in Soft Robotics
Ellen Roels,* Aleix Costa Cornellà, and Joost Brancart
1. Introduction
Materials are at the core of soft robotics, directly influencing the functionality, overall performance, and even the manufacturing process of soft robotic systems. As the field progresses, researchers are developing increasingly specialized materials for specific applications. Furthermore, the trend toward incorporating more embodied intelligence in soft robotic designs drives the use of
more complex material combinations, making well-considered material selection and understanding their properties essential for a successful implementation. However, obtaining these material properties can be challenging. Manufacturers and materials developers often report limited relevant data for soft robotics, and use different metrics, making material comparison difficult. Even when data are available, there is no consensus within the research community on how materials should be characterized specifically for soft robotics and many other fields. This lack of standardization creates several challenges: researchers waste resources repeatedly characterizing common materials, crossstudy comparisons become unreliable, and replication of results becomes difficult. These obstacles ultimately slow innovation and limit collaboration opportunities across research groups. Several studies have identified standardization and reproducibility as key challenges in the broader field of soft robotics.[1–5] While there is currently no comprehensive standardized framework for the design and characterization of soft robotics, researchers have made progress in specific subdomains of the field. For instance,[6] developed performance metrics for fluidic rotational actuators, and[7] proposed a naming scheme for thermo-active actuators.[6,7] Also, several aspects of a proposed datasheet for variable stiffness actuators could be useful for soft robotics.[8] Specifically for materials,[9] another study established a database for uniaxial tensile data of elastomers measured according to the ASTM D412 standard, enabling hyperelastic material model fitting for finite element analysis (FEA).[9] While this is an important step forward in reducing redundant testing, hyperelastic analysis alone is an incomplete characterization of materials for soft robotics, as it only describes quasielastic material properties. To address these limitations, we propose a comprehensive testing and reporting framework specifically designed for elastomers, the most commonly used materials in soft robotics, as illustrated in Figure 1. This framework incorporates four key aspects of characterization: quasielastic mechanical properties, viscoelastic mechanical properties, thermal stability, and processing properties. Each of these aspects has been chosen for its relevance to soft robotics. Quasielastic mechanical properties provide data on the static stress–strain behavior of elastomers, enabling engineers to develop accurate material models for simulating soft robots.
