For instance, consider soft grippers that repeatedly grasp and release objects. Their performance depends on how the elastomer recovers from deformation. Stress-relaxation experiments capture the time-dependent response to sudden strain changes, while compression set measurements provide insights into their long-term deformation under sustained loads. Viscoelastic properties are thus relevant for predicting the behavior under realworld conditions.
2.3. Thermal Stability
Temperature variations significantly affect the mechanical properties of elastomers, which in turn impact soft robotic performance. A soft robotic actuator operating in an environment with fluctuating temperatures must maintain its predictable behavior, thus, knowing how the mechanical properties change with temperature is beneficial. In this framework, three key parameters define the useful temperature range, depending on the elastomer type. The glass transition temperature (Tg) is the temperature below which a material shifts from an elastic to a brittle state, thus leading to a lower bound for operational temperatures in soft robotics. For thermoplastic elastomers, the melting temperature (Tm) serves as the upper limit, as the material loses structural integrity and becomes a viscous liquid. In contrast, thermosetting elastomers are generally more thermally stable and have an upper temperature limit that can be defined by their degradation temperature. Since these transitions are not immediate at these key temperatures, a safety margin is used.
2.4. Processing Properties
Processing properties determine how an elastomer can be fabricated into soft robotic components. For thermoplastic elastomers, not only is the melting temperature important for ensuring proper flow during extrusion processes such as 3D printing, but temperature also influences the viscosity of the melt. For thermosetting elastomers, the curing time, which is highly temperature-dependent, dictates the fabrication process. These processing characteristics are important for selecting and optimizing manufacturing methods. These selected properties capture both the intrinsic mechanical behavior and the practical considerations necessary for designing, simulating, and fabricating soft robotic systems. By integrating these aspects into a standardized characterization framework, we provide a robust basis for material selection in soft robotics.
3. Material Characterization Framework
The framework is designed to be comprehensive enough to quantify the essential properties relevant to soft robotics while remaining practical for implementation in typical research environments. Several principles guided its development. First, accessibility is prioritized by selecting testing methods that can be implemented using equipment typically available in soft robotics laboratories. Second, the testing procedures are in line with international standards where applicable, which ensures compatibility with existing practices in materials science. As discussed earlier, the focus is placed on material properties that
have direct implications for the performance of soft robots, particularly under dynamic or varying conditions. This framework, therefore, enables meaningful comparisons between different elastomers for specific soft robotic applications. Ten materials are selected to demonstrate the wide applicability of the framework. Specifically, seven thermosetting elastomers from Smooth-On (Dragon Skin 20, Dragon Skin 30, Ecoflex 00-20, Ecoflex 00-30, Ecoflex 00-50, Mold Max 14NV, and Mold Star 30) and two commercial TPU filaments (Filaflex 60A from Recreus and Cheetah from NinjaTek) are characterized, as these materials are commonly used in the field.[13–17] Beyond these conventional elastomers, also FsCOBMI689 is characterized, an in-house developed bio-based covalent adaptable network previously used to manufacture selfhealing soft robots.[18] This demonstrates that the proposed framework can effectively characterize traditional elastomer categories (both thermosetting and thermoplastic) as well as more specialized materials developed for advanced soft robotic applications that do not necessarily fall within these two traditional categories. This selection allows validation of the framework across different elastomer classes, while providing a useful reference dataset for the soft robotics community. The following sections detail the specific methodologies for each test and present the results for all ten materials.
3.1. Quasielastic Mechanical Properties
Although elastomers are inherently viscoelastic, their behavior is frequently approximated as hyperelastic for FEA. This approach is capable of predicting the nonlinear elastic behavior under large strains, but does not take into account its time dependency. Nevertheless, it is often sufficient for applications in soft robotics. Uniaxial tensile testing is the most common characterization method to determine properties such as the elastic modulus, tensile strength, and ultimate elongation. Shore hardness, a widely reported material property that measures resistance to indentation, is also discussed as it provides engineers with a simple yet valuable indicator of material stiffness. In this framework, tensile testing is complemented with a uniaxial compression test to get a more complete overview of the quasielastic material properties. This data is then used to create a hyperelastic material model for finite-element simulations.
3.1.1. Uniaxial Tensile Analysis
Uniaxial tensile analysis provides comprehensive insights into material behavior under extension and serves as the primary data for fitting hyperelastic material models. However, the viscoelastic nature of elastomers introduces complexity as their mechanical properties are influenced by the strain rate. Previous studies have demonstrated that variations in strain rate can lead to modulus changes exceeding 20%, indicating the importance of maintaining a uniform strain rate.[19,20] To ensure meaningful material comparisons, the ASTM D412 standard is adopted for the framework, which specifies a strain rate of 450 mm min 1 and dogbone-shaped samples, offering several advantages. A well-defined testing protocol enables direct comparison with
