rrelation could potentially offer improved accuracy, they introduce challenges such as lens distortion, resolution limitations, and marker tracking difficulties at high strains. Additionally, contact-based extensometers may influence material response
through local stress concentrations or slippage. Such deviations from the standard should be noted in the datasheet for transparency. While thermoplastic and thermosetting elastomers can both reach high strain values, thermoplastic elastomers often exhibit partial irreversible plastic deformation at high strains. Thermosetting elastomers can reach significantly lower moduli thanks to the nature of their amorphous backbone (absence of crystalline domains) and chemically crosslinked nature. Figure 2A shows the complete stress–strain curves for three representative materials: Dragon Skin 30 (thermosetting), Filaflex 60A (thermoplastic), and FsCO-BMI689 (CAN). These graphs highlight key differences in material behavior: Dragon Skin 30 exhibits a gradual stiffening response typical for thermosetting elastomers, while Filaflex 60A shows a higher initial stiffness followed by a yielding behavior.
3.1.2. Uniaxial Compression Analysis
