3.1.3. Shore Hardness
Shore hardness provides a simple and practical means of comparing elastomers and is frequently used by manufacturers of commercial polymers. In many cases, the Shore hardness value is even directly incorporated into the material’s name, as is the case for several polymers characterized in this study. Although both Shore hardness and uniaxial compression tests are compressive, they are fundamentally different. Uniaxial compression applies a uniform load across the entire sample surface, whereas Shore hardness is determined via localized point indentation. The ASTM D2240 standard defines multiple Shore hardness scales, of which types A and 00 are the most relevant for soft robotics, and 00 is the softest of the two. However, differences in indenter geometry and applied force between scales make direct comparison across scales difficult. The Shore hardness measurements can be conducted on the same sample geometry as used for the uniaxial compression tests. Notably, measured values sometimes deviate from manufacturer specifications. For instance, while the Shore hardness of Dragon Skin 30 was measured as 31A, the printed Filaflex 60A samples show a hardness of 71A, highlighting the importance of direct measurement. While empirical relationships have been proposed to estimate the Young’s modulus from Shore hardness values, these formulas are only suitable to give a first indication and are not sufficiently reliable to replace direct uniaxial testing in soft robotics.[22] Despite its limited information content compared to more comprehensive tests, Shore hardness remains valuable due to its widespread use, ease of measurement, and low cost. While the durometers used for this study (Sauter HB0 100-0 and Sauter HBA 100-0) cost 130 euro each, basic devices start around 30 euro.
3.1.4. Hyperelastic Model
The data obtained from the tensile and compression tests can be used to create hyperelastic material models for finite element simulations. The selection of the best-fitting model (e.g., Ogden, Neo-Hookean, Mooney–Rivlin) depends on the specific elastomer. To determine the most appropriate model, multiple models should be evaluated, with the one exhibiting the best fit being selected. Several finite-element software packages, such as Abaqus and ANSYS, enable direct parameter fitting from test data. Alternatively, Marechal et al. provided a Python script for model parameter estimation that does not rely on external software packages.[9] While fitting the model parameters on stress–strain data obtained using an extensometer typically leads to satisfactory models, this is not the case when the fit is done on data obtained without an extensometer. Such data often results in models that overestimate material stiffness, potentially introducing errors in simulations. One solution is to iteratively improve the model by simulating the stress–strain tension and compression test using FEA and adjusting the material model such that the simulated experiment fits the experimental data. A Python script provided in the Supporting Information automates this process using Abaqus. Analyzing the hyperelastic model results after optimizing them using Abaqus (Table 2) shows the differences in model fit across the materials. While most elastomers demonstrate a good fit with the Ogden second-order model, Cheetah was best fitted with a second-order polynomial, and FsCO-BMI689 model had the best fit with a first-order polynomial model. The resulting model parameters of the best-fitting model(s) are incorporated in the proposed material datasheet. This comprehensive approach, combining tensile and compressive data, ensures a robust characterization of mechanical properties for finite-element simulations.
