the materials. Viscoelasticity refers to materials that exhibit both viscous and elastic characteristics when undergoing deformation. Unlike purely elastic materials that instantly return to their original shape after deformation, viscoelastic materials show time-dependent strain recovery, stress relaxation under constant strain, and creep under constant stress. This behavior governs the time-dependent response under cyclic or sustained loading. In soft robotics applications, viscoelasticity is especially important as the materials are often subjected to cyclic loading (e.g., during walking or grasping) or constant loading (e.g., while holding an object). It affects the control of soft robots by introducing hysteresis, creep, and rate-dependent deformation, which complicates precise deformation control. Unlike purely elastic materials, viscoelastic materials have a phase lag between the applied forces and deformations. Additionally, energy dissipation due to viscoelasticity influences dynamic tasks, requiring well-thought control approaches. This viscoelastic behavior is strongly influenced by the load amplitude, frequency, and environmental conditions (e.g., temperature) and can be conceptually modeled using combinations of springs (elastic elements) and dashpots (viscous elements) arranged in series or parallel. The simplest models, such as the Maxwell model (spring and dashpot in series) and the Kelvin–Voigt model (spring and dashpot in parallel), are generally insufficient to capture the full complexity of viscoelastic behavior. Therefore, we propose to use a generalized Maxwell model, as shown in Figure 3A. Each parallel branch represents a different relaxation time constant, allowing the model to capture behavior across multiple time scales. The isolated spring denoted by E∞ represents the equilibrium
modulus and captures the fact that the elastic component dominates the response for large displacements or at very long time scales. In practice, a first- or second-order model (meaning one or two Maxwell elements in parallel with the isolated spring) is often sufficient to approximate the viscoelastic behavior of elastomers used in soft robotics. A related phenomenon observed in elastomers is the Mullins effect, which shows a reduction in stress upon repeated loading and unloading cycles. This is a form of stress softening and is relevant in applications where materials undergo repeated deformations. For unfilled elastomers, this softening is typically fully recoverable over time, meaning that the material gradually regains its original mechanical properties. This shows that it can be interpreted as part of the viscoelastic response and is therefore not considered separately here. However, in composite (filled) elastomers, the Mullins effect becomes partially unrecoverable, leading to permanent material changes that may impact long-term performance. If this framework were to be extended to such materials, the Mullins effect would need to be analyzed independently.
3.2.1. Stress Relaxation
Stress relaxation tests provide valuable insights into the viscoelastic behavior of elastomers by monitoring the decay in stress after applying a rapid strain change. Although no single standard covers the viscoelasticity of all elastomers, the proposed protocol is based on the ISO 3384 standard. In this standard, a cylindrical sample with a diameter of 13 mm and an initial thickness of 6 mm is strained to 25% compressive strain, and the stress decay is observed. Whereas the standard specifies to reach this strain in 30–120 s, we propose to do this faster to minimize relaxation effects during the loading phase. To obtain optimal results, the strain should be applied on a timescale an order of magnitude faster than the material’s relaxation time. The stress relaxation may occur so rapidly that it becomes challenging to capture accurately, and 150 mm min 1 was used during this work due to the physical limits of the instrument. After reaching the target strain, a constant strain is maintained during the isostrain hold period, where the decay in stress due to the visoelasticity is captured over time. The duration of the isostrain hold is selected to ensure that both the immediate and delayed relaxation behavior are fully observed, in this case, 3 h proved to be sufficient for all tested materials. The viscoelastic behavior is characterized by fitting the experimental data with an nth-order Prony series corresponding to a Maxwell model of the same order
