3.3. Thermal Stability
The mechanical properties of elastomers are highly temperature dependent, which directly affects their performance in soft robotics. Although the properties described earlier are measured at room temperature, these tests can be repeated at different temperatures to define an operational window. While minor temperature variations (provided the material is not near its critical thermal transitions) often have a negligible effect, larger variations (>10 °C) can lead to substantial and sometimes abrupt changes. It is therefore useful to propose a temperature window in which the properties do not change significantly.
These thermal stability limits are defined by three key parameters: the glass transition temperature (Tg), the melting temperature (Tm), and the thermal degradation temperature. Each of these transitions plays an important role in determining the operational range in soft robotic applications
3.3.1. Glass Transition
The glass transition temperature marks the point below which mobile phase elastomers transition from a viscoelastic, rubbery state to a hard and brittle, glassy state with a low fracture strain. Most elastomers used in soft robotics have a Tg well below room temperature, which allows for their characteristic flexibility. Tg can be determined using differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) according to ASTM D3418. In a DSC scan, Tg is identified as a sigmoidal change in the baseline due to a change in heat capacity as the polymer transitions from a rigid glass to a flexible elastomer upon heating. Figure 4A shows the glass transition for two of the reference materials: Dragon Skin 30, and Filaflex 60A. In PDMS-based Dragon Skin 30, although the Tg is not very pronounced, it is observed to be around 121 °C. As the mechanical properties of a material change significantly below its Tg, it can be used as a lower usability limit for soft robotic applications. For soft robotic applications, we recommend staying at least 20 °C above Tg.
3.3.2. Melting
For many semicrystalline elastomers, the crystalline domains transition into a viscous liquid above the melting temperature. Unlike low-molecular-weight molecules, the melting transition in polymers occurs over a range of temperatures rather than at a sharply defined point due to inherent structural heterogeneities such as defects, branching, and molecular weight distribution from the polymerization process. A precise definition for uniform reporting is thus necessary, and we propose reporting the peak melting temperature as the representative value. This value is obtained via differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) following the ASTM D3418 standard, which is the same standard as used for the glass transition, but the recommended sample mass (5 mg for Tm, 10 mg for Tg) differs between the two measurements. Tm is particularly important for thermoplastic elastomers because these materials become a viscous liquid above this temperature. As illustrated in Figure 4B, the DSC curve for Filaflex 60A displays a melting range with a well-defined peak at 214 °C. To prevent partial melting, a safety margin of 20 °C from the melting point should be adhered to as a rule of thumb. Some block copolymeric elastomers, such as SBS and SEBS, do not exhibit a distinct Tm. Instead, they are characterized by a high glass transition temperature in their rigid blocks. For these materials, the high Tg of the hard phase governs the upper thermal limit. For thermosetting elastomers, particularly semicrystalline types like PDMS-based materials, the crystalline domains have a melting temperature that can significantly influence mechanical properties. For instance, Figure 4A shows the melting transition of Dragon Skin 30 at 43 °C, indicating that its crystalline phase is in its liquid state at room temperature. As this Tm is
