3.3.3. Thermal Degradation
When polymers are overheated, they undergo degradation processes such as depolymerization, side group elimination, and backbone scission. These processes fundamentally alter the polymer’s chemical structure, leading to increased brittleness, and changes in physical properties. The molecular weight, a parameter representing the average mass of the polymer chains, is reduced by chain breakage. The formation of smaller, volatile molecules is accompanied by a measurable mass loss of the sample, which can be quantified using thermogravimetric analysis (TGA). Although TGA does not provide information on the specific phenomena behind the degradation process, it determines the temperature at which mass loss occurs. Note that in addition to thermal degradation, polymers are also susceptible to degradation from other environmental factors such as UV radiation, humidity, and oxidation, which are not further explored within this framework. The proposed TGA procedure follows the ASTM E2550 standard and is conducted under a nitrogen atmosphere to avoid oxidation. The degradation temperature is reported as the temperature at which 2% mass loss occurs, as shown in Figure 4C. FsCO-BMI689, Dragon Skin 20, and Filaflex 60A, respectively, have a 2% degradation temperature of 191, 250, and 176 °C. For elastomers susceptible to moisture absorption, such as Filaflex 60A, a pretest drying step (e.g., 5 h isothermal at 45 °C) is recommended to ensure the observed mass loss is due to actual degradation rather than moisture evaporation. For thermosetting elastomers, the degradation temperature typically defines an upper operational limit. For safe operation in soft
robotics, it is advised that the application temperature remains at least 50 °C below the degradation temperature, as degradation already starts before it is visible in the TGA measurement. Table 4 provides a comprehensive overview of the thermal properties for the characterized materials, illustrating the diverse thermal behaviors across different elastomer types and listing their operational temperature limits.
3.4. Processing Properties
While processing properties of elastomers do not directly influence the operational performance of soft robots, they are important for the reliable fabrication of these components. Processing methods vary significantly between elastomer classes, requiring a clear understanding of their differences. Thermoplastic elastomers are primarily characterized by their melting behavior, whereas the processing of thermosetting elastomers relies on curing kinetics. Covalent adaptable networks exhibit features of both, as they can be processed through thermal methods as well as through curing.
3.4.1. Melting
For thermoplastic elastomers, thermal processing methods such as 3D printing and injection molding require heating the material above its peak melting point. As discussed in Section 3.3.2, semicrystalline elastomers exhibit a melting range rather than a discrete melting temperature. While the peak melting temperature is an important reference point for processing, the onset temperature and the width of the melting peak are more critical in determining optimal processing parameters and can be determined using the ASTM D3418 standard as well. In the case of Filaflex 60A, the onset melting temperature (Tm,onset) is 194 °C and the end temperature of the
