3.4.2. Curing
For thermosetting elastomers, the transition from liquid to solid occurs through curing. This is a chemical process in which crosslinks are formed, distinguishing it from the physical transitions of melting and solidification. For thermosetting elastomers, curing is an irreversible process. However, for covalent adaptable networks, which consist of reversible crosslinks, this process becomes reversible at higher temperatures. The kinetics of curing are strongly temperature dependent; higher temperatures generally accelerate the crosslinking reactions and reduce the overall curing time. An important practical consideration during the curing process is the mixing viscosity. A sufficiently low mixing viscosity is practical for casting processes, as it improves mold filling and reduces the entrapment of air bubbles; therefore, we propose to add the mixing viscosity to the datasheet as well. For the characterized thermosetting elastomers, the mixing viscosity is in the range of 100–101 Pa s.
A critical moment in the curing process is gelation, defined as the point at which a continuous polymer network is formed, resulting in a pronounced change in viscoelastic properties of the material. It is important to note that gelation is not equivalent to having a fully cured network, as some unconnected monomers or oligomers may still be present. Curing can be monitored using rheometry, where the evolution of the storage modulus (G 0) and loss modulus (G 00) is tracked over time using an oscillatory rotational measurement, as well as the viscosity. As there is no suitable standard available, we propose to define full curing of the network as the moment when the storage modulus reaches 99% of its final value. Figure 5B illustrates the evolution of these two moduli during the curing process of Dragon Skin 30 at 25 °C and at 60 °C. At 25 °C, the curing process takes 216 min, which is considerably lower than the manufacturer’s reported curing time of 16 h. At 60 °C, the curing time is reduced by roughly an order of magnitude to 18 min. The curing time of platinum-cured elastomers (e.g., Dragon Skin, Ecoflex, Mold Star series) in function of temperature was studied in detail by Yap et al., they reported that the mechanical properties of these cured polymers are unaffected by the curing temperature.[23] Also for FsCO-BMI689, which has a considerably longer curing time (3738 min at 25 °C), increasing the temperature to 60 °C speeds up the curing process to 1698 min. However, since the structure of this CAN relies on a temperature-dependent chemical equilibrium, curing at elevated temperatures does not necessarily yield the fastest route to equilibrium conversion at room temperature. Based on these observations, we propose reporting curing times at both 25 and 60 °C, as further temperature increases provide only marginal time savings without additional practical benefit. Nevertheless, curing times at different temperatures can be added if desired. An overview of these c