5. Discussion
This work introduces a comprehensive framework for elastomer characterization tailored specifically to soft robotics applications. The framework addresses four key aspects of material behavior: quasielastic mechanical properties, viscoelastic mechanical properties, thermal stability, and processing properties. By presenting these characteristics in a standardized datasheet format, the framework not only improves the reproducibility of material characterization, but also facilitates accurate material modeling and selection in soft robotics research. The quasielastic mechanical properties, derived from uniaxial tensile and compressive tests, provide fundamental information on the stress–strain behavior of elastomers under static or slowly varying loads. These tests enable researchers to verify whether a material meets the desired stress, strain, and modulus criteria for a given application, while facilitating the development of hyperelastic models for numerical simulations.
