Viscoelasticity is particularly important in soft robotics, as materials often undergo repetitive deformations. This framework captures basic viscoelastic behavior through stress relaxation experiments and compression set, providing a useful baseline to compare different materials. Thermal stability characterization is equally important, defining the operational temperature range of elastomers. By determining degradation or melting temperatures and glass transition points, researchers can ensure material integrity across different operational conditions. The fourth aspect of this framework is the processing properties. For thermoplastic elastomers, understanding the melting temperature range and melt viscosity is essential, while the mixing viscosity and curing dynamics are the most important properties for thermosetting elastomers. Understanding these properties helps optimize manufacturing processes and ensure material consistency. While the proposed framework offers a robust approach to material characterization for soft robotics, researchers should also consider its limitations. First, the approach is limited to uniaxial testing. Currently, there are no standardized protocols for biaxial testing of polymers, nor are these test setups widely available. These could provide a more comprehensive understanding of the material behavior under multiaxial loads. Also, shear tests are not included in the framework. To the author’s best judgment, there is no representative standard available for elastomers that can be performed on a uniaxial UTM, an instrument commonly found in robotics labs. Adding biaxial and shear experiments would lead to better hyperelastic models, but for many cases, the improved accuracy is expected not to be worth the added complexity. Another limitation is the assumption of having isotropic material properties. While usually valid for molded parts, this may not hold true for 3D-printed components.[25] Additionally, the framework does not address the influence of environmental factors such as humidity, radiation, or UV
exposure on the mechanical properties. Nevertheless, if the equipment is available, the same tests can be repeated at various environmental conditions when relevant for the application. While this framework provides a baseline for viscoelastic characterization that can be performed on commonly available testing equipment, it does not capture the full spectrum of viscoelastic behavior. Additional experiments, such as creep-recovery tests, cyclic tests, or tests performed at different strain rates, strain amplitudes, or temperatures, provide a more holistic understanding. Frequency-dependent techniques such as DMA can further complement this by determining the storage and loss moduli across a wide range of frequencies, amplitudes, and temperatures. Similarly, this approach only takes into account unfilled elastomers, additional experiments are required to address the Mullins effect in composite or filled elastomers. However, since this is material and application specific, we have refrained from incorporating them in this framework, but recommend researchers to perform their own tests specifically tailored towards their use case. Fatigue behavior, critical for industrial applications, is not fully explored due to the time-intensive nature of comprehensive testing involving thousands or even millions of deformation cycles. Future extensions of this framework should consider incorporating cyclic loading tests at varying strain/load amplitudes to establish fatigue thresholds for different elastomers. Additionally, studying the evolution of mechanical properties throughout the fatigue lifetime would be interesting. While the framework provides guidelines to determine an operating temperature range, it should also be noted that even temperature changes within this range can influence the mechanical properties. For materials where this influence is large, the mechanical analysis should be repeated at different temperatures if relevant for the application. A more global influence of thermal effects on the mechanical properties can be studied using a temperature sweep in dynamic mechanical analysis. Specialized properties like friction, conductivity, chemical resistance, and biocompatibility are not included, as these are highly application specific. Instead, the framework aims to create a standardized database that facilitates meaningful comparisons of elastomers across different soft robotic applications. This generality makes the framework also applicable to more specialized elastomers, but can be extended to include more specific information. For CANs such as FsCO-BMI689, the quasielastic and viscoelastic properties remain relevant for soft robotics, although they are expected to show a stronger temperature dependence due to the kinetics of the reversible bonds. For the thermal stability, the relevant transition for the upper operational limit is the gel transition, which can be determined using rheometry. This gel transition also influences their processing properties, since reprocessing depends on bond kinetics rather than melting. While the framework focuses specifically on properties relevant for soft robotics, the complex chemical structure and bond kinetics of such materials could be characterized more directly through spectroscopy or further DSC studies.[11] Future research could expand the framework by incorporating more comprehensive testing protocols, exploring environmental interactions, and developing more extensive characterization methods. This work directly contributes to the ongoing
