6. Conclusion
In this study, we have introduced a comprehensive and standardized framework for the characterization of elastomers specifically tailored to soft robotics applications. This framework integrates important aspects of material behavior, including quasielastic and viscoelastic properties, thermal stability, and processing characteristics, into a datasheet. Using standardized testing protocols and widely available equipment where possible, our approach enhances reproducibility and transparency in data reporting while bridging the communication gap between roboticists and material scientists. A broad range of materials used in soft robotics, consisting of thermosetting elastomers, thermoplastic elastomers, and a covalent adaptable network, were characterized to demonstrate the applicability of the proposed methodology. The framework enables the development of accurate hyperelastic models for finite-element simulations, facilitating more reliable design and performance predictions for soft robotic systems. Despite covering a broad range of useful material properties, we acknowledge limitations in areas such as fatigue characterization, biaxial and shear testing, and the influence of environmental factors. If deemed relevant for a specific application, the frameworks can be extended to include these. The adoption of this standardized characterization framework is expected to streamline material selection, foster collaborative research, and accelerate advancements in soft robotics. By establishing a robust foundation for systematic material evaluation, this work opens avenues for further exploration into dynamic material behavior and interdisciplinary integration, which are essential elements for the evolution of soft robotics.
